# WHAT IT IS
#   In a **laptop orchestra**, multiple musicians each play their
#   own laptop in real time as a coordinated ensemble, often
#   triggering MIDI sequences, algorithmically-generated music,
#   or pre-recorded audio.  The hard problem:  keeping every
#   laptop's clock + beat-phase synchronized so that when
#   performer A triggers a MIDI loop at beat 1 of measure 5,
#   performer B's MIDI loop also lands on beat 1 of measure 5
#   (despite the network's variable latency, each laptop's clock
#   drift, and the round-trip lag through the audio system).
#
#   Harmonia uses **Ableton Link** — the canonical real-time
#   network-synchronization protocol shipped by Ableton with
#   their Live DAW since 2016, now an open-source library at
#   github.com/Ableton/link adopted across the music-tooling
#   industry by Cycling74 Max/MSP, Native Instruments Maschine,
#   PreSonus Studio One, Image-Line FL Studio, Steinberg Cubase,
#   Reason Studios Reason, and dozens of community projects —
#   to maintain a shared beat-phase + tempo across every
#   instance running on the LAN.  The Polish RobertBendun/
#   linky_groups extension layered on top adds the
#   "synchronized start / synchronized stop" group-coordination
#   semantics needed for ensemble-level cueing.
#
#   Each harmonia instance:
#
#     1. Joins the Ableton Link session (`rusty_link::AblLink`)
#        to inherit the global tempo + beat-phase
#     2. Opens a MIDI output (default OS MIDI device + Linux/
#        macOS virtual port named "Harmonia") via `midir::
#        MidiOutput`
#     3. Loads a state file (`harmonia_state.bson` in the
#        current dir) containing the "blocks" the performer
#        has authored — each block is a MIDI file, an audio
#        file, a shared-memory channel pointer, or an
#        algorithmic music generator
#     4. Serves an HTTP/htmx UI on the configured port
#        (default `8080`) where the performer can trigger
#        blocks
#     5. Listens for `linky_groups` group-synchronization
#        events to coordinate group-wide cues
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from src/harmonia.rs clap-
#                       derive `Cli` struct;  extracted via raw.
#                       githubusercontent.com fetch of src/
#                       harmonia.rs)
#
#   harmonia [OPTIONS]
#
#   Options:
#     -h, --help                     Show help
#     -V, --version                  Print version (includes the
#                                    canonical multi-component
#                                    Version::default() string
#                                    from src/version.rs)
#     --disable-link                 Don't start the Ableton Link
#                                    connection (useful for
#                                    single-laptop testing without
#                                    polluting the LAN's Link
#                                    session)
#     --open                         Open the UI in the default
#                                    browser after the HTTP server
#                                    starts listening
#     -i, --ip <IP>                  IP address to bind the UI
#                                    HTTP server to
#                                    [default: 0.0.0.0]
#     -p, --port <PORT>              Port for the UI HTTP server
#                                    [default: 8080]
#     --no-color                     Disable colored log output
#                                    (overrides the NO_COLOR
#                                    environment variable)
#                                    [default: false]
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   `RobertBendun/harmonia` declares a **direct** dependency on
#   `midir` in its `Cargo.toml`, and `src/harmonia.rs` directly
#   imports the typed primitives via `use midir::MidiOutput;` /
#   `midir::MidiOutputPort` /  `midir::MidiOutputConnection` and
#   (on Unix) `midir::os::unix::VirtualOutput` for the
#   automatic-virtual-port behavior on Linux + macOS.
#
#   `Boddlnagg/midir` is **THE canonical Rust MIDI library** —
#   Patrick Walton's reference cross-platform MIDI I/O library,
#   wrapping the platform-native MIDI APIs into a unified Rust
#   API:
#
#     • **Linux**         — ALSA Sequencer + JACK MIDI (via the
#                            `jack` Cargo feature)
#     • **macOS**         — CoreMIDI (the Apple-native MIDI
#                            framework)
#     • **Windows**       — WinMM (the Windows Multimedia
#                            Extensions MIDI API, since Windows
#                            3.1) + WinRT MIDI (the modern
#                            UWP API)
#     • **BSD**           — JACK MIDI (via the same `jack`
#                            feature)
#     • **Web / Browser** — Web MIDI API (the W3C-standardized
#                            browser MIDI API, via wasm32
#                            compilation)
#
#   The library exposes:
#
#     • Typed `MidiInput::new(client_name)` /  `MidiOutput::
#       new(client_name)` typed device-client builders
#     • Typed `input.ports() -> Vec<MidiInputPort>` /
#       `output.ports() -> Vec<MidiOutputPort>` typed port-
#       enumeration
#     • Typed `input.port_name(port) -> Result<String, Error>`
#       /  `output.port_name(port)` typed port-name resolution
#     • Typed `input.connect(port, port_name, callback,
#       data) -> Result<MidiInputConnection, ConnectError>`
#       typed input-port subscription that calls back with
#       typed `(u64 timestamp, &[u8] message_bytes, &mut U
#       user_data)` for every incoming MIDI message
#     • Typed `output.connect(port, port_name) -> Result<
#       MidiOutputConnection, ConnectError>` typed output-port
#       handle + `connection.send(message) -> Result<(),
#       SendError>` typed message-send
#     • Typed `os::unix::VirtualInput::create_virtual(name)`
#       /  `VirtualOutput::create_virtual(name)` typed virtual-
#       port creation (Linux + macOS — these ports are visible
#       to other applications via ALSA Sequencer / CoreMIDI as
#       if they were physical devices)
#     • Typed `MidiInputPorts` / `MidiOutputPorts` typed
#       enumerable port collections
#     • Typed `ConnectError` / `InitError` / `SendError` /
#       `PortInfoError` typed errors
#
#   `Boddlnagg/midir` is the MIDI library behind **every modern
#   Rust music project**:
#
#     • **icsga/Yazz**             a wavetable synthesizer
#     • **arteme/pod-ui**          GTK+ UI for Line6 POD MIDI
#                                  controllers
#     • **rwtnb/Drumsthesia**      Synthesia-style learn-to-play
#                                  app for electronic drum kits
#     • **devaloop-labs/devalang** music-as-code DSL compiler
#     • **camshaft/euphony-rs**    music composition environment
#                                  for programmers
#     • **coignard/o2**            Rust port of the ORCΛ
#                                  esoteric livecoding language
#                                  (a Mark Foulds + Devine Lu
#                                  Linvega original — the
#                                  influential 2D-cellular-
#                                  automaton-style livecoding
#                                  environment ported across
#                                  dozens of languages)
#     • **RobertBendun/harmonia** (this very project)
#     • **simonredfern/SimonSaysSeeq** Norns + Rust music
#                                     livecoding sequencer
#     • **takemo101/sine-mml**     MML (Music Macro Language)
#                                  → MIDI compiler
#     • **legato-dsp/legato**      Rust DSP framework with
#                                  MIDI integration
#     • **LeoRiether/FPGRARS**     RISC-V simulator with MIDI
#                                  output (every RISC-V `ECALL`
#                                  to system call 31 emits a
#                                  MIDI note — a unique
#                                  pedagogical demo)
#     • **reedrosenbluth/oscen**   audio-synthesis dataflow
#                                  framework with MIDI control
#                                  surface
#     • **NeoTecDigital/MusicTheory-rs** music theory library
#                                       with MIDI output
#     • **glittercowboy/MUSE**     MIDI-driven generative-music
#                                  framework
#     • **thebasedcapital/ane-synth** modular synthesizer
#     • **barrelorgandiscovery/virtualbookplayer** virtual barrel
#                                                  organ MIDI
#                                                  bookplayer
#     • **ianlintner/instrument_to_midi** guitar-to-MIDI
#                                         converter via pitch
#                                         detection
#     • Plus dozens of community DAW plugins, synthesizers,
#       sequencers, music-livecoding environments, MIDI
#       monitors, MIDI converters, MIDI bridges, network-MIDI
#       gateways, and physical-controller-to-MIDI translators.
#
#   MIDI itself is **the universal music-technology
#   interoperability standard** — invented in 1983 by the joint
#   effort of Roland (Ikutaro Kakehashi) + Sequential Circuits
#   (Dave Smith) + Oberheim + Yamaha + Korg + Kawai, MIDI 1.0
#   has been the lingua franca between every electronic
#   musical instrument, every digital audio workstation, every
#   computer-music notation editor, every music livecoding
#   environment, every hardware sequencer, every drum machine,
#   every MIDI controller, every guitar-to-MIDI converter,
#   every synthesizer module, every General MIDI sound module,
#   every electronic stage piano, every MPE-capable expressive
#   controller, every MIDI 2.0-compatible device since the
#   2020 MIDI 2.0 standard ratification, and every Web-MIDI-
#   capable browser application.  The MIDI 1.0 wire protocol
#   (over 5-pin DIN, USB-MIDI, and now RTP-MIDI over UDP/IP
#   for network-MIDI) carries the typed `NoteOn`, `NoteOff`,
#   `PolyAftertouch`, `ControlChange` (with the standard 128-
#   slot CC-number space + the canonical `CC#1 = Modulation
#   Wheel`, `CC#7 = Channel Volume`, `CC#10 = Pan`, `CC#11 =
#   Expression`, `CC#64 = Sustain Pedal`, `CC#74 = Filter
#   Cutoff` mappings), `ProgramChange`, `ChannelAftertouch`,
#   `PitchBend` (14-bit), and the typed `SysEx` (System
#   Exclusive) escape messages for vendor-specific extensions.
#   MIDI 2.0 extends to 32-bit per-note values, MPE (MIDI
#   Polyphonic Expression) standardized per-note articulation,
#   and bidirectional handshake-based property exchange.
#
#   Verified via:
#     gh api repos/RobertBendun/harmonia/contents/Cargo.toml
#       → [[bin]] name = "harmonia"  test = false  bench = false
#                  path = "src/harmonia.rs"
#       → [[bin]] name = "linky_groups"  test = false bench = false
#                  path = "src/playground.rs"
#       → [package] license = "AGPL-3.0"
#     raw.githubusercontent.com RobertBendun/harmonia main src/
#         harmonia.rs
#       → //! Synchronized player for laptop orchestra
